{"product_id": "220700", "page": 1, "page_order": 7, "recommended": false, "date": "4 January", "text": "The last \"good\" RPG Maker, before everyone was ready to forsake their heritage, throw Don Miguel under the bus, and hold their hand out to the Internet expecting a hefty paycheck for either something this program ought to have included from the get-go, or else for something so cheap that it looks like it was made with...well, with this program.\nI'm not sure I understand the perverse fetish for requiring Steam to be open to launch the program. The less programs I have open suits me just fine, and Steam barely even opens when it's supposed to open.\nLet me give an example for the uninitiated and those living in willful ignorance: The RPG Maker series uses character classes. Y'know, fighter, mage, cleric, etc. But it doesn't give an in-built menu with the program to change those classes easily. You have to event it. It's this shortsightedness that has cemented Enterbrain, or ASCII, or whatever these obstinate, minimum-effort drones call themselves these days.\nIf you want to have a game with any functionality beyond a Dragon Quest clone, then you're gonna have to scrounge around and backup all the scripts you can find, unless you want to devote a decade of your life to learning the obscure programming language that is Ruby. Programming is a detail-oriented skill, and these \"detail-oriented\" people had the foresight to not properly curate or permit redistribution of their scripts, so in a few years it'll all be 404 links clogging up search engines. I guess they consider their hard work to be disposable like that.\nDo yourself a favor don't get this until you've absolutely outlined your project from start to finish and know all the tools you'll need beforehand, because otherwise you'll have been overcharged (even ten bucks is a laugh for the limited resources the program comes bundled with) just to release a half-finished game, or else to not release anything at all. So when someone does finish a game, and they make that game available to you, free of charge, take a moment to appreciate the passion, the pure integrity and commitment that these people have been blessed with. These virtues saw them through a thankless task, and they deserve thanks.", "hours": 0.5, "username": "Zetawilk", "products": 266, "early_access": false}
