{"product_id": "27900", "page": 2, "page_order": 4, "recommended": false, "date": "2020-06-15", "text": "Controls and Movement are very clunky and not very well thought out.\nExample: You move slower walking backwards and to the sides, which also applies in the air, making air control very awkward.\nAnother example is the use key for pressing buttons and picking up keycards being the same as for the red Attract-Power (LMB), which they could have easily put onto it's own key like E or something. This leads to you sometimes pulling yourself towards somewhere, instead of pressing a button or picking something up.\nStory and Setting are generic and not very interesting. The bad voice acting doesn't help either.\nThe only thing making the puzzles challenging is either the physics not cooperating and making it unnecessarily difficult to execute the solution or having to guess what you are supposed to do, because the game does not teach you the required mechanics properly.\nThere's 2 main enemies you encounter throughout the game.\nSome flying drone balls called \"Tracers\" that do not present any challenge at all, because you can easily walk past them and even if they manage to hit you, you will barely take damage. You have to actively walk into them if you want to die. Even if there is more than 1, they will just bunch up to a bigger ball and still be no challenge at all.\nThe second main enemy are the stationary turrets. They are the complete opposite of the drones. One shot from them will instantly kill you. Most of the time you are supposed to distract them with some object and then sneak past them, but 90% of the time that just ends up not working, because either the physics don't cooperate or they decide to see you anyways.\nThere's one smaller explosive orb enemy in one of the latter levels and in the final battle, but they are equally unfair, cause they are way faster than you and once they catched up, they just get stuck around your feet and it is impossible to get them off from you before they explode and just kill you.\nEvery Level basically looks the same and I guess they started running out of ideas for \"puzzles\" in the later parts of the game, because they start reusing some of the earlier ones in the second half. It's also just not very interesting to walk through the same corridors over and over again. You just walk from puzzle to puzzle until you reach the end of the level just to repeat that again in the next level.\nThere is several other things that add up to making this an unbearable experience to play.\nLoading screens take ages (which with the fact that you die alot from all kinds of things, gets very frustrating)\nAlso NO AUDIO SLIDERS AT ALL. You have to go into the windows mixer if you don't want the game to blast your ears out.\nThere's many more things like this, but I don't feel like listing up everything.\nI don't know why I'm writing up this much, because the game certainly doesn't even deserve the time of getting a review written, but I genuinely dislike every aspect of this game and it's one of the worst games I forced myself to play through.\nPlease don't unironically buy this game.", "hours": 12.6, "username": "Dacciox", "products": 357, "early_access": false}
