{"product_id": "314020", "page": 3, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2021-02-27", "text": "Morphopolis is a point-and-click puzzle game that attracts attention entirely hand-drawn and artistically appealing.\nThe game was first developed in 2013 for mobile platforms and received highly positive reviews.\nInspired by games like Machinarium and Tiny Bang Story, Morphopolis is a game about transformation and exploration.\nWe take on the role of an aphid in the game that takes you on an adventure full of puzzles in the fantasy world of insects.\nWith point-and-click gameplay, Morphopolis presents the world of plants and insects in a magnificent visuality.\n.\n.", "hours": 3.8, "username": "Ogi", "products": 575, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "314020", "page": 3, "page_order": 6, "recommended": false, "date": "2021-02-25", "text": "This is another \"art-not-game\" \"game\" dumped on Steam by artists who presumably had a restraining order taken out by their local art gallery and had to resort to inflicting their \"art\" on Steam instead, confusing CS:GO playing PC gamers with art snobs.  Nice work.\nWe're left with a kind of clicker \"game\" that involves a lot of hand drawn art.  Click and drag things sometimes onto insect things, I don't know. It doesn't make a lot of sense.  My card idler went nuts which is why I have 65 hours on this non-game.\nTo be really fair, the hand drawn art is okay.  It's a shame it was wasted on something that is neither art nor video game.   Regardless, this is Steam.  For video games. On PC.  Not for art school dropouts who couldn't get a minute in an art gallery to inflict their failure on.   Not a game, therefore, cannot recommend to gamers, on Steam, the platform for video games.", "hours": 65.5, "user_id": "76561198030784015", "username": "Obey the Fist!", "products": 6169, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "314020", "page": 3, "page_order": 7, "recommended": false, "date": "2021-02-21", "text": "It's pretty and the sound design and music are nice, but there's an awful lot of pathfinding issues for a game that's completely on rails, movement is glacially slow and requires holding down the mouse button toward your destination rather than just clicking (which makes the slow movement even more awkward), screen transitions are also very slow (which coupled with the bad pathfinding means you'll spend a bunch of time watching screen transitions as you accidentally switch screens and then wait to switch back), and the hidden object sections are more like just object sections as most of them are in pretty obvious. The puzzles are okay.", "hours": 2.7, "username": "this-maciek-moment", "products": 682, "early_access": false}
