{"product_id": "246960", "page": 3, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-06-28", "text": "When a DLC (or a standalone expansion) comes out to an already great game, you can just hope it'll be more of the same, with some minor twists. GSTD:RotOL provides you with exactly that experience - one of the twists being maybe a bit unexpected.\nThe incredible visual world of the first game is back in full force, and the naval theme gave the graphics artists some extra legroom, and the two sea-specific levels (Mistral Reefs and Spring Tide Bay) have some really breathtaking sights, even by GSTD standards. The music is a clever combination of three new tunes and some of the old ones, and two of the three new songs are really memorable, while the third is just good. Level design is as megalomaniac as ever, and the gameplay didn't change much, although there are a few new elements, I especially like the tri-color projectile mechanic (ie. reds hurts Cute Giana, yellow hurts Punk, blue hurts both). There's a change in the difficulty, however.\nAfter all the curses GSTD got for the difficulty, especially on World 3, one would think Black Forest would back down a bit. But they did the contrary, actually - 4-1 feels like a direct continuation of 3-9, with the exception of the opening scene, which I found hilarious. Then 4-2 and 4-3 gradually ramps the difficulty upwards, 4-4 dips a little bit, then comes 4-5, the aptly named Black Forest, which is probably the most difficult non-Boss (or more like non-dragon) level in the both games.  I applaud the creators for it, although when I was trying to complete it on Hardcore, I was not exactly applauding :D\nThen, after the fearsome-looking but actually rather tame 4-6, we get to our single boss, the Owlverlord. After the Black Forest, I was wondering how this guy will rate compared to Gurglewocky, but fortunately (or unfortunately), this boss is much easier than the mighty dragon, and while it's harder to figure out than Hansel & Gretel or Octor Freud, once you got the right responses to its moves the fight gets a lot easier. Some of its attacks are spectacular and fun - but in the end, very easy to dodge. It was a slight letfown, but at least no loss of hair :)\nSummary - if you liked the original GSTD, you need Rise of the Owlverlord as well. It's just as great as the first game.", "hours": 33.0, "user_id": "76561197991465987", "username": "gbors", "products": 1116, "early_access": false}
