{"product_id": "230820", "page": 3, "page_order": 9, "recommended": false, "date": "2021-10-10", "text": "Would I recommend this game? Honestly, yes and no. If you enjoy point and click adventure games full of puzzles than this might be your game however I didn't find a lot of the puzzles exactly intuitive. I tried playing the game without any kind of guide but I really couldn't make it past the first \"map,\" or really start the story line. I think the story line is decent... if you stay with it. At one point I stopped listening to all of the dialog because it just sort of drones on. There are plenty of guides out there for folks that want to give it a real try but are stuck so don't feel you are alone.\nFor my achievement hunters out there: make sure you get to all of the bonus collections and such prior to going into the last portal (the game will prompt you) because once you go in, there is no way of getting back to \"wrap things up.\" Additionally... the last duel is able to be skipped however you will want to do it for an achievement. Lastly, make sure you say good bye to everyone... you will want to.", "hours": 12.1, "username": "Lyra Marie", "products": 134, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "27900", "page": 3, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2019-02-02", "text": "Twin Sector is the game that wouldn't possibly exist without Portal. I mean, cough, a female protagonist wakes up in a facility, without really knowing what's going on, then being greeted by a robotic voice (less robotic in English than German, I should note) and then being told what to do, which of course, turns out to be a bad idea. SOUNDS FAMILIAR, DON'T IT?\nNow, meet our hero Ashley Simms aka Number Nine aka StonedFace. You'll be seeing her face lots and I mean it. She is all over the main menu, the loading screen, the game's boxart, thumbnail, cutscenes, EVERYWHERE. We get it, she's the only character worth a damn, but cmon, you could at least have hired a better voice actor for her or give her more complex facial animations, something to show us that you really cared about her! But nope, instead we get the same picture every loading screen, one of the worst voice actresses in a video game ever (even worse in German) and this is meant to be their marketing chick. Yeah no, you dropped the ball on that much too hard. So what's in store regarding plot and gameplay?\nLife on the surface is not possible due to critical conditions and the remaining survivors, including Ashley, are put into cryosleep until they can go back to their ordinary lives. But suddenly, we wake up, with a large fraction of our mind erased, in a CONSIDERABLY TIGHT jumpsuit that really marks our *cough* assets. Aside from that, we have a neat-looking pair of gloves that grants us the ability to pull (red) and throw (blue). Instead of portals, you have to use the limited energy stored in your gloves to solve puzzles based on physics, height, gravity and dodging. To be fair, that is indeed an innovative concept and works rather well most of the time, some puzzles are cleverly designed and the subtle use of the soundtrack fits the atmosphere perfectly. In general, the controls are simple, easy to master and to learn, as the challenges lie within the countless obstacles you have to overcome.\nAs previously stated, there aren't many voice actors present in the game and not many characters to begin with and they still couldn't come up with some sort of workaround to make them sound more natural. The presentation feels too stale, the texture work is repeating itself from level to level, the story doesn't try to expand on what is already known, the ending is a cliffhanger building up for a sequel that obviously never came, the cutscenes are blocky and years behind the 2009 standard, you can find grammatical errors in subtitles and there is no replay value except the unlockable Hardcore mode that lets you play with quicksaves disabled. Meh. You will too encounter bugs such as pickups not being highlighted, flames not being rendered or objects getting stuck and THE GAME PROMPTS YOU TO SNEAK AROUND TURRETS WHEN IT'S NOT EVEN POSSIBLE. Ugh...\nI completed it twice, on both modes and I have to admit, the second run was more pleasurable to do as I knew how the mechanics worked perfectly. But it remains a budget project that I cannot recommend UNLESS you want to be reminded how great Portal is. It's really good. Go buy that instead. If you own it, but a copy for your friend and play it in coop.", "hours": 11.8, "username": "–Øedly –Øed.ÊöóËµ§Ëâ≤@Tsundere-Tiddy", "products": 910, "early_access": false}
