{"product_id": "342450", "page": 1, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "19 August, 2021", "text": "This is an entertaining game even if it is short.  There's an event referenced in the game that can't ever happen, which is weird.  And the \"romance\" in the game is more-or-less instantaneous.  This is inevitable because the game is short.\nMost of the bad reviews seem to be about the length of the game, but the game is less than $2 on sale.  For that price, it's fine.\nThe art is very well done.  The first few playthroughs of the game are exciting.  After that, it's a little bit of a slog if you want to get all the endings, which I did.  For such a short game, there's no reason not to get all of the endings.\nBuy this game when it's on sale.  Just be aware that you're only going to get a limited amount of playtime out of it.", "hours": 2.3, "user_id": "76561198042901813", "username": "cowgod14", "products": 503, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "342450", "page": 1, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "29 April, 2021", "text": "Warning: Spoilers regarding character interaction and story located near the end of the second paragraph.\nTL;DR is game pretty but bad, 3/10\nI like both visual novels and choose your own adventure stories, so I figured that despite the mixed reviews this one got I'd still be pretty happy with it. I was wrong. It's not completely terrible and it's obvious that some real work went into it based on the fantastic art and suitable music, but what starts as an interesting story quickly falls apart when you realise just how short a single playthrough can be. I finished my first run in about 20 minutes, with making some mistakes and having to retry some choices, and when I did finish it I was left immensely unfulfilled, as if I'd seen a single episode of an anime expecting more only to be told \"Nope, that's it for these characters.\" Clearly the intent was to have the player keep replaying it and discover every single ending to make up an appropriate amount of in game time for the price tag, but after getting 8 of them and learning that many contain the same scenes and dialogue (more so than most CYOA titles I've played) I think it'd be a mind numbing slog to push through all the content this game does have. After letting it idle long enough to get my last card drop, I think I'll be done with it. I will say though, that for the CYOA portions there was a nice element of suspense whenever you found yourself in a new situation.\nIt certainly doesn't help that the romance angle is somewhat flawed at best, and not just for how quickly the two characters seem to fall in love. I thought it was weird but alright given the short length per playthrough up until I got an ending that made me realise just how awful Gavin really is. He went from lonely outcast in need of a friend to weird guy who thinks he's entitled to a tradwife but has put no effort into being someone that any woman would like, let alone the one of his dreams. Furthermore, he seems to be taking advantage of a naive teenage girl who's just lost her only surviving parent and I think he knows it. I wouldn't be surprised to find out he watched her while she slept for a while before waking her up. The guy is a creep, plain and simple. There's no real way to tell him no either, which is gross.\nAnother big issue I have with this is the fact that our heroine, the woman warrior who some of us are excited to play as, is quickly made into a supporting character while Gavin gets to be the star and does all the cool stuff. That's not even close to empowering, which an experience like this should be. She's also presented as extremely one dimensional and boring with no personality to speak of. This game misses the mark pretty badly all around in my opinion, with it's few highlights not being nearly enough to outweigh all the bad. Might be worth it when it's on sale for the achievements and trading cards, but otherwise don't bother.", "hours": 1.5, "user_id": "76561198196490709", "username": "Ithaqua", "products": 638, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "342450", "page": 1, "page_order": 4, "recommended": false, "date": "20 March, 2021", "text": "In Sword Daughter, you play as knight and Lady Tyrna. You and your father have hired some Caravan members to escort both of you across a mighty desert on a journey, but even with extra protection, everyone is ambushed by Orcs! You are knocked unconscious and miraculously survive thanks to a Half-Elf Warden, Gavin, who is on a journey of his own. Reluctantly joining you on your quest for vengeance, you both get in way more trouble than you could have ever anticipated.\nWhile there are multiple endings, an awful lot of them are very similar with copy/paste dialog. The music was nothing special and the story has so many holes it might actually be swiss cheese. The absolute worst part of Sword Daughter is the romance. Tyrna and Gavin fall in love\nand she is absolutely ready to go ahead and move in with him and get married before he finishes the first sentence.\nThe best ending is technically a bad ending but honestly, I was ready to burn the entire place to the ground anyway.", "hours": 1.8, "user_id": "76561198201613371", "username": "Zelrune", "products": 361, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "314020", "page": 4, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2021-01-27", "text": "This game is a hidden gem imho. The walking is sometimes a bit too slow paced for my taste, and sometimes it wasn't obvious what to do; but that's easily forgiven because there's a button to get a hint if you want it, the puzzles were neither too easy nor too difficult, the music is enjoyable and relaxing, and the art is simply delightful. I quite enjoyed it and at the end I was wishing for more. I bought this game on sale and don't regret it, and if there's ever a sequel I'll happily pay full price to support the devs.", "hours": 2.2, "username": "GleeEyedRaven", "products": 320, "early_access": false}
