{"product_id": "275080", "page": 4, "page_order": 6, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-09-13", "text": "...is a business tycoon game. Build and expand your postal service enterprise, opening offices and managing staff, vehicles and service coverage while competing with other organizations.\nYou start with a single post office, and can open additional offices as new locations periodically become available. Each office will cover an amount of city blocks based on the office size. You must then hire clerks and mail sorters, as well as upgrade each office with various objects.\nA fleet of vehicles may be purchased and assigned to either pick up or deliver mail, packets or postal cards. Each vehicle has a different speed, fuel cost, carrying capacity and quantity of blocks it can be assigned to. Vehicles and office upgrades are unlocked from stars you get from completing objectives, delivering priority parcels or having a good weekly performance when compared to competitors.\nThere are three office sizes, the larger they are and the more vehicles, employees and wider coverage you get. Every day, new office locations may unlock, others may have been acquired by competitors. Office coverage overlap is inevitable and required, as you will need to specialize each office (mailing, parcel delivery or post cards), the limited vehicle and employee capacity preventing from you from having only a few large offices that do everything. As time passes, the three cities on the map expand with additional city blocks, unlocking either more offices or potential customers.\nYou're given access to a good variety of vehicles. As their run around the map, you can see how much capacity they are using (although regular mail seems to count as 0% no matter how many you have), making it easy to see when a vehicle is unable to support its workload and needs to be replaced with a larger one. You can see your competitor's offices on the map, as well as their vehicle type and cargo type, making it simple to gage their coverage and service offering, useful considering their company information is confidential, beyond their total delivery quantity.\nCompetitors cannot be dealt with in any way: you cannot hinder them, you cannot buy them out, they are there and that's it. Reports are extremely vague and give you no indicator on how to better compete, it just says you lost points due to competition. There's no information on prices either, no feedback to know if you're too low, and if customers complain you're too high, it doesn't clarify if it pertains to letters, packets or express cargo. This makes the competitive aspect of the game very lame and inactive, so you'll quickly outright ignore competitors presence beyond hurrying to expand faster in order to deliver more mail than they do.\nOffices and vehicles sizes cannot be upgraded. If you need a larger office, you must sell your existing office and repurchase it by selecting a larger model. This is infuriating, as staff and vehicles are locked to your offices, forcing you to repurchase all your vehicles, staff and office upgrades all over again and set routes and tasks from scratch. Once an office has received all its upgrades, which can be unlocked and purchased very early in the game, there is nothing more to do with it, besides occasionally replacing used vehicles or hiring additional staff (assuming you haven't maxed it out already) for rush periods during holidays.\nThe isometric map is fairly small, consisting of three towns, no landscape to speak of (flat green fields with scattered pine trees, no mountains or lakes of any kind). You will quickly reach a point where you have nothing more to do besides hope that, hours later at max speed, additional city blocks are built requiring you to repeat the \"build office, hire staff, purchase vehicles, set tasks\" routine you go through with every new office you open. This gets boring very quickly, as there's a terrible lack of variety, you'll see all the game has to offer quickly and won't feel inclined to replay it.\nI don't see how I can recommend this game. It just feels lackluster, a pityful fraction of what a game the likes of\nachieved years ago. Much like other games by the same developer (such as\nand\n), it is a pale imitation of a better game, so you shouldn't bother spending a penny on it. I am not playing this one ever again.\n‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî", "hours": 6.8, "compensation": "Product received for free", "user_id": "76561198030788488", "username": "Cracktus Jack", "products": 625, "early_access": false}
