{"product_id": "27900", "page": 4, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-11-07", "text": "Twin Sector is a fascinating title. Many would be quick to compare it to the Portal series, and I can understand why. The premise is you being stuck in a facility with an AI buddy navigating you through puzzles, while you make use of a dual functioned device. However, the more I played Twin Sector, I increasingly found that most comparisons between Twin Sector and Portal are merely ignorant, pointing out only very slim similarities, while ignoring the bigger picture.\nTwin Sector is really a game about isolation, delving into the mind of a woman thrown into a strange, cold world that does not look inhabitable whatsoever. All the while, she is being bossed around by disembodied male voices, bossing her around but without having any warmth or liveliness to them. In a world where she is the only person, she has to solve all of the problems in the facility. But... do these problems even exist? The only evidence of their existence is the robotic men who speak to her through the intercoms. For all we, the player, know, these issues may not even be real, and they may be lying to her, to exploit her and to display power over her.\nThis is where Twin Sector shines. Just the dilemma that it presents, the horror of the situation, is enough to set it apart from Valve's shoddy competitor.", "hours": 6.9, "user_id": "76561198042332015", "username": "Foolish Person", "products": 79, "early_access": false}
