{"product_id": "342450", "page": 2, "page_order": 5, "recommended": false, "date": "2019-11-30", "text": "I don't know why this game is called Sword Daughter. It refers to the player character, Tyrna, even though she's just a side character in the adventures of dreamy half-elf Gavin. In the first route I found, they have about two conversations, both of which have Tyrna saying that she wants to go get revenge for her father and is annoyed that Gavin's saying it's too dangerous, and then Tyrna bumps her head and Gavin says \"I'm taking you to my home\" and they kiss. Ugh.\nEvery route that doesn't end with Tyrna dying or being cursed, ends with her hooking up with Gavin, no matter how little sense it makes. If you say you'll go on without him, he'll stalk you and show up a paragraph later like this was his idea all along. If you split up, Gavin will find you as soon as is narratively convenient. If you try to separate yourself from Gavin, the narrative will eventually punish you with one of the aforementioned deaths or curses.\nThis wouldn't be nearly so bad if Gavin was a better person and a better character. He's a pretty boring character, with his only character traits being badassery, falling in love with Tyrna for ill-explained reasons, and attempts to control Tyrna that keep being framed as nothing more than concern. Even though he pretty consistently criticizes and insults her any time she goes against what he says, initiates intimacy without bothering to ask for consent, and generally assumes he knows best in the relationship. Like Tyrna's a child he just has to protect. And don't get me started on his constant, obnoxious efforts to pamper a woman who clearly wants to be treated as an equal.\nAnd, of course, the narrative supports this. It's okay that Gavin tells Tyrna what to do, because he's right; he's an awesome elf, and she's just a puny human girl. It's okay that Gavin keeps ignoring Tyrna's requests to shoulder her share of the load, because she bonked her head. It's okay that Gavin smooches her without making sure that this surly young woman wants a smooch, because the internal narration has been hinting that Tyrna has the hots for Gavin with all the subtlety Michael Bay could muster, and no need to have her actually say any of that. Ugh.\nAnd then there's the plot. Tyrna tries to sneak into the orc camp? Gavin somehow snuck in behind you, even if he was cowering from a stampede of oxen and you have the cloak of concealment. Tyrna confronts the leader of the brigands? Gavin shows up before Sword Daughter has to draw her sword and lets her spectate. Find an evil cultist guy? Gavin fights him, chases him into the lake, and drives him into the water beetles. When there's a big fight scene Gavin usually lets Tyrna participate a little, though there's decent odds she'll be left to spectate by some event outside his control...and, of course, Gavin always does the badass stuff. I haven't found the ending where Tyrna confronts the orc who killed her dad, but given how every other plot point of import has wound up, I expect some kind of contrivance to give Gavin an excuse to take Tyrna's revenge for her.\nAfter all, who picks up a game called Sword Daughter hoping to play a badass warrior woman? Nah, they want to play a damsel in distress playing at warrior before retiring to be a nice waifu for the badass half-Legolas dreamboat.\nThe art is pretty, though.", "hours": 1.1, "user_id": "76561198079727113", "username": "GreatWyrmGold", "products": 451, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "324610", "page": 2, "page_order": 2, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-08-25", "text": "It has potential, good voice acting and nice art, but it is too much of a repeat-experience with too little differences and hints on that there are actually 4/5 different endings that in the end it's not worth it unfortunately. Not afwul, more like a 'meh'. But there are many other games to better play.", "hours": 1.0, "username": "king-of-sass", "products": 267, "early_access": false}
