{"product_id": "324610", "page": 2, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-07-11", "text": "It's a short point and click game which suffers from disjointed storytelling.\nWhen the game starts out you have no idea what you're supposed to do or even what the basic premise is. After five minutes of clicking and exposition I finally figured out that there's a guy about to visit his mother-in-law and he's asking a shopkeeper for advice about a present and how to approach the (unfriendly) mother-in-law.\nDepending on what things you click on you get a different story. There are also different dialogue options and a few different endings, but which ending you get is essentially random. Completing the game takes less than five minutes and then you can try another pattern of choices.\nBut the whole story is pretty mundane. Even the \"best\" ending is rather underwhelming. Yes, the game is inexpensive but there's not much to it either.", "hours": 0.9, "user_id": "76561198032573928", "username": "Murgen", "products": 826, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "342450", "page": 2, "page_order": 7, "recommended": false, "date": "2019-10-06", "text": "Things move way too fast. Not as in, the story is too short. The problem is that everything is rushed. For example, you meet a guy who you think is kinda rude, and I chose to leave him behind. But not only does he follow me, but shortly after the two characters start passing saliva out of nowhere.\nIt's fine that it's a short game. Sometimes games don't need hours and hours of gameplay to be good. But it's not a good excuse for a rushed plot and relationships, which is a result of sloppy writing.\nIf you don't mind people falling in love out of nowhere, than you might like it. The music and the artwork is very good so that might be good enough for some. For me though, the writing was too cringy.", "hours": 0.3, "username": "AnimeJunkee", "products": 396, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "324610", "page": 2, "page_order": 4, "recommended": false, "date": "2017-07-06", "text": "There's the nugget of something interesting in here, but the game itself fails badly on execution. It's no big spoiler to mention that the game relies on a short, repeating loop of story. This can be and has been done well before in both games and movies, but here, it's a disaster. There simply isn't enough variation in either actions or dialogue to keep it engaging. It works the first handful of times because you can choose different conversations, but after that it's simply maddening repetition. There's no clear indication of what you need to do to \"win\", and in fact even after trying dozens of combinations, I had to look up a guide to find the exact chain of events to get the final ending. This ending had a somewhat surprising twist, but it was nowhere near enough to make up for the tedium of trying to get to it. I don't know that I could even recommend this game if it were free, just because the work/reward ratio is awful. Again, there's a piece of a story that could be good, but it was botched horribly.", "hours": 2.8, "username": "Torchiest", "products": 845, "early_access": false}
