{"product_id": "281580", "page": 4, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-12-19", "text": "Being a virtual pilot for so many years on many platforms, I must admit that I was pleasantly surprised by WOE.\nIt is a perfect match with my Thrustmaster Hotas X, but be advised that led must be green for rudder, and nose wheel activation. Contrary to red status, for MSFS pilots.\nUsing patience and some trial and error for customizing keys and buttons, via the menus for \"action  and single mission\", will be very rewarding.\nOunce all your strategic commands are a few fingertips away, it is only then you shall enter the campaign mode.\nOtherwise you will be blown to pieces, in no time.\nTaking about time, no annoying timers are present, and neither ridiculous artificial  \"walls\" to deal with.\nA convinient autopilot(quite abrupt) is on board when requested, taking care of landings ,take offs, and waypoints navigations.\nHaving my OE still on Windows XP, WOE and other \"old\" great stuff, runs magnificently.\nPilots, lights, surface controls, gear and so forth, are well detailed and animated.\nAn ejecting seat comes standard, but will fail your mission.\nI even think that it fails it even if you met your objectives. I will confirm later.\nNapalm explosions and other special effects, are truly way advance for the time.\nIt was actually released on May 24th, 2006.\nMany levels of difficulty are possible, as armament configurations for aircrafts and tasks at hand.\nTime advance is practical on those long distances traveled between strategic waypoints.\nI enjoy this \"game\" so much, that I bought the official DVD, so that I could have the nice box, manual,  and disc back up just in case.\nSadly, I do not own a Track IR device for it. Someday I will.\nVeterans of the Ace Combat series  will be right at home, except for the high resolutions of playing consoles.\nDon't get me wrong, considering the age of WOE, it is very good.\nAgain, way ahead of it's time.\nSo long fellow virtual pilots.\nPS: Occasionnaly deploying airbrake during tight maneuvers, is a very effective method in certain dogfights.\nYou all probably knew that...", "hours": 38.5, "user_id": "76561198079853514", "username": "adenis123", "products": 91, "early_access": false}
