{"product_id": "342450", "page": 4, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-06-30", "text": "I went in thinking it was going to be a bad otome. But actually the heroine is significantly stronger than the reviews imply, more competent, more experienced, and less defined by elf romance. If this was an actual otome, the main character would be a ray of sunshine. Admittedly, I have not yet taken stupid defenseless paths, and I really don't want to.\nYou can end the game without swearing eternal love for the elf, seizing nearly every moment of sword chopping glory entirely for yourself. I charged the enemies first, thought of tricks first, and compromised my own safety to protect his dumb butt first. The elf's not a guide. You don't actually follow him, because he's stuck with whatever decisions you make. He talks big, but he's entirely dependent on you to make every choice. It's great.\nI haven't reached the homemaker ending yet. (I don't want to) I like being an equal as friends or otherwise. In terms of 80s misogyny, I was shook, which was upsetting, but it was brief. It's possible that I would have been shook as a dude in that scenario. I was never slapped. In one playthrough, I was entirely praised, and never heard a word edge-wise.\nA lot of readers to VNs have experienced significantly worse, for games made entirely for girls. At least I felt like a hero, I was resourceful, successful, romance not critical to my adventure, and I had eyes.\nThe story's ok. It's not nearly as confusing as reviewers made it sound. Pretty normal high fantasy.\nPaths are really short, SUPER short, but the art is wonderful. In most visual novels, the sample pictures may be the last cgs you get. Nearly every panel of this thing has new art, and more importantly fully drawn, romantic illustration backgrounds.\nOn sale, it's absolutely worth the price.", "hours": 0.6, "username": "Doldrum", "products": 537, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
